l  . This surname is common among Native Americans, namely the Cheyenne River Sioux in SD."]},{"name":"Braye","meanings":["English (Sussex): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Braye</i>. Its origin is unknown but it might derive from Breton <i>bregh</i> ‘fine, brave’."]},{"name":"Brais","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Aldea, Andre, Cecile, Fernande, Stephane.","French: altered form of   Bray  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Marie</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moira","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Máire , now used throughout the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705212,"age":2,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705213,"age":24,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705216,"age":70,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Bray was born about 1618, in Leicestershire, England. She married John Rowlett in 1637. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1700, in Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America, at the age of 83."},"et":{"about 1618–1700":"umbes 1618–1700","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1618–1700":"1618–1700","1679":"1679","about 1618":"umbes 1618","1700":"1700","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"umbes 1653","1618":"1618","2 June 1679":"2. juuni 1679","1715":"1715","1637":"1637","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America"},"fi":{"about 1618–1700":"noin 1618–1700","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1618–1700":"1618–1700","1679":"1679","about 1618":"noin 1618","1700":"1700","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"noin 1653","1618":"1618","2 June 1679":"2. kesäkuuta 1679","1715":"1715","1637":"1637","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America"},"fr":{"about 1618–1700":"environ 1618–1700","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1618–1700":"1618–1700","1679":"1679","about 1618":"environ 1618","1700":"1700","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"en